I am writing to express my disappointment regarding a recent experience at one of your locations. As a loyal Costco member, I was surprised and frustrated to learn that my son was denied entry while attempting to shop on my behalf, despite presenting my valid membership card.

On that particular day, I was unwell and unable to visit the store myself, so I entrusted my son with my membership card to purchase essential items. However, your staff refused to allow him entry, stating that the card could only be used by the actual member. While I understand the importance of maintaining membership integrity, I find this policy to be unnecessarily rigid and impractical in situations like mine.

Many other retailers allow family members to shop on behalf of the primary member, especially when there is no fraudulent intent. Costcoâ€™s strict enforcement of this rule seems unreasonable and creates unnecessary inconvenience for paying members. It would be more customer-friendly if Costco considered making reasonable exceptions, particularly in cases where a family member is simply helping due to illness or other valid reasons.

I hope you take this feedback into consideration and revisit this policy to better serve your members.
